<file path="README.md">
  1: # Google Calendar & Gmail MCP Server
  2: 
  3: A Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that provides Google Calendar and Gmail integration for AI assistants like Claude.
  4: 
  5: ## Features
  6: 
  7: ### Calendar
  8: - **Multi-Calendar Support**: List events from multiple calendars simultaneously
  9: - **Event Management**: Create, update, delete, and search calendar events
 10: - **Recurring Events**: Advanced modification capabilities for recurring events
 11: - **Free/Busy Queries**: Check availability across calendars
 12: - **Smart Scheduling**: Natural language understanding for dates and times
 13: - **Inteligent Import**: Add calendar events from images, PDFs or web links
 14: 
 15: ### Gmail
 16: - **Message Search**: Query Gmail with flexible search filters (is:unread, from:, subject:, etc.)
 17: - **Profile Management**: Get account information (message count, thread count, email address)
 18: - **Multi-Account Support**: Use multiple Gmail accounts with separate OAuth tokens
 19: 
 20: ## Recent Updates (v1.4.9)
 21: 
 22: **Performance & Reliability:**
 23: - 🚀 Dynamic label ID resolution (L6) - Scripts now work across accounts with different label hierarchies
 24: - ⚡ Sequential API optimization - ~500ms latency reduction per operation
 25: - 📦 Batch filter operations - 10-100x speedup for bulk Gmail tasks
 26: 
 27: **Tooling & Infrastructure:**
 28: - ✅ Comprehensive label resolution guide ([docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md](docs/LABEL-RESOLUTION-GUIDE.md))
 29: - 🧪 Parametrized test expansion (25 → 30+ test cases)
 30: - 📋 New changelog system ([docs/changelog/](docs/changelog/)) tracking all improvements
 31: 
 32: **Testing:**
 33: - 492/494 tests passing (99.6%)
 34: - Reduced technical debt with shared utilities in `lib/gmail-*.mjs`
 35: - CLAUDE.md updated with latest patterns and utilities
 36: 
 37: See [CHANGELOG](docs/CHANGELOG.md) for complete v1.4.9 release notes.
 38: 
 39: ## Quick Start
 40: 
 41: ### Prerequisites
 42: 
 43: 1. A Google Cloud project with the Calendar API enabled
 44: 2. OAuth 2.0 credentials (Desktop app type)
 45: 
 46: ### Google Cloud Setup
 47: 
 48: 1. Go to the [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com)
 49: 2. Create a new project or select an existing one.
 50: 3. Enable the [Google Calendar API](https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/library/calendar-json.googleapis.com) for your project. Ensure that the right project is selected from the top bar before enabling the API.
 51: 4. Create OAuth 2.0 credentials:
 52:    - Go to Credentials
 53:    - Click "Create Credentials" > "OAuth client ID"
 54:    - Choose "User data" for the type of data that the app will be accessing
 55:    - Add your app name and contact information
 56:    - Add the following scopes (optional):
 57:      - `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events` and `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar`
 58:    - Select "Desktop app" as the application type (Important!)
 59:    - Save the auth key, you'll need to add its path to the JSON in the next step
 60:    - Add your email address as a test user under the [Audience screen](https://console.cloud.google.com/auth/audience)
 61:       - Note: it might take a few minutes for the test user to be added. The OAuth consent will not allow you to proceed until the test user has propagated.
 62:       - Note about test mode: While an app is in test mode the auth tokens will expire after 1 week and need to be refreshed (see Re-authentication section below).
 63: 
 64: ### Installation
 65: 
 66: **Option 1: Use with npx (Recommended)**
 67: 
 68: Add to your Claude Desktop configuration:
 69: 
 70: **macOS**: `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`
 71: **Windows**: `%APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json`
 72: ```json
 73: {
 74:   "mcpServers": {
 75:     "google-calendar": {
 76:       "command": "npx",
 77:       "args": ["@cocal/google-calendar-mcp"],
 78:       "env": {
 79:         "GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS": "/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
 80:       }
 81:     }
 82:   }
 83: }
 84: ```
 85: 
 86: **⚠️ Important Note for npx Users**: When using npx, you **must** specify the credentials file path using the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
 87: 
 88: **Option 2: Local Installation**
 89: 
 90: ```bash
 91: git clone https://github.com/nspady/google-calendar-mcp.git
 92: cd google-calendar-mcp
 93: npm install
 94: npm run build
 95: ```
 96: 
 97: Then add to Claude Desktop config using the local path or by specifying the path with the `GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS` environment variable.
 98: 
 99: ### First Run
100: 
101: 1. Start Claude Desktop
102: 2. The server will prompt for authentication on first use
103: 3. Complete the OAuth flow in your browser
104: 4. You're ready to use calendar features!
105: 
106: ### Multi-Account Support (Test Mode)
107: 
108: This server supports multiple Google accounts in test mode with automatic token management.
109: 
110: **Setup both accounts:**
111: 
112: Account 1 (Initial):
113: ```bash
114: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
115: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
116: npm run auth
117: ```
118: 
119: Account 2 (Same file, different account key):
120: ```bash
121: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
122: export CALENDARMCP_TOKEN_PATH=~/.config/google-calendar-mcp/tokens.json
123: npm run auth  # Authenticates second account in same tokens.json
124: ```
125: 
126: **Verify both accounts:**
127: ```bash
128: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="./credentials.json"
129: npm run verify-tokens
130: ```
131: 
132: Outputs token status, expiry times, and account validity for all authenticated accounts.
133: 
134: **Important Notes:**
135: - Both accounts stored in single `tokens.json` file with separate keys
136: - Tokens expire after 7 days in test mode (Google requirement)
137: - TokenManager auto-refreshes tokens 5 minutes before expiry
138: - Set `ACCOUNT_MODE` environment variable before running the server to select which account is active
139: 
140: ### Re-authentication
141: 
142: If you're in test mode (default), tokens expire after 7 days. If you are using a client like Claude Desktop it should open up a browser window to automatically re-auth. However, if you see authentication errors you can also resolve by following these steps:
143: 
144: **For npx users:**
145: ```bash
146: export GOOGLE_OAUTH_CREDENTIALS="/path/to/your/gcp-oauth.keys.json"
147: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
148: npx @cocal/google-calendar-mcp auth
149: ```
150: 
151: **For local installation:**
152: ```bash
153: export ACCOUNT_MODE=test
154: npm run auth
155: ```
156: 
157: **To avoid weekly re-authentication**, publish your app to production mode (without verification):
158: 1. Go to Google Cloud Console → "APIs & Services" → "OAuth consent screen"
159: 2. Click "PUBLISH APP" and confirm
160: 3. Your tokens will no longer expire after 7 days but Google will show a more threatning warning when connecting to the app about it being unverified.
